1
00:00:00,001 --> 00:00:03,001
Website Optimization

2
00:00:02,560 --> 00:00:05,560
Numerous research and case studies have shown that the longer a site takes to respond,

3
00:00:07,360 --> 00:00:10,360
the more visitors will abandon it.

4
00:00:09,600 --> 00:00:12,600
No matter your site's focus, providing the best experience for your visitors is the main goal,

5
00:00:15,040 --> 00:00:18,040
so optimizing it for speed is critical.

6
00:00:18,080 --> 00:00:21,080
In this lesson, you will learn what website optimization means,

7
00:00:22,160 --> 00:00:25,160
which elements can impact performance, how to test your site's speed, and how to improve it.

8
00:00:28,320 --> 00:00:31,320
Web performance pertains to the user experience of low time and runtime.

9
00:00:34,160 --> 00:00:37,160
As a practice, web performance involves measurable factors,

10
00:00:38,320 --> 00:00:41,320
such as a page's loading time and the time it takes to become interactive,

11
00:00:43,120 --> 00:00:46,120
as well as the user's perception of how long it took.

12
00:00:47,520 --> 00:00:50,520
What affects performance?

13
00:00:50,000 --> 00:00:53,000
Multiple components determine a site's speed,

14
00:00:52,960 --> 00:00:55,960
software, network conditions, hardware, each calculated by standard metric.

15
00:00:59,520 --> 00:01:02,520
The way to achieve high performance scores is to optimize each of these moving parts.

16
00:01:05,040 --> 00:01:08,040
Let's start with software, which covers code and content.

17
00:01:09,920 --> 00:01:12,920
WordPress themes define the pages' content structure.

18
00:01:13,840 --> 00:01:16,840
Some design elements, like colors, have no effect on performance,

19
00:01:16,960 --> 00:01:19,960
whereas others, from fonts and graphic assets to carousels and pop-ups,

20
00:01:22,640 --> 00:01:25,640
could tank your site's speed.

21
00:01:24,720 --> 00:01:27,720
Selecting newer, more performant file formats is a good practice when dealing with media and fonts.

22
00:01:31,200 --> 00:01:34,200
Images especially play a key role in website optimization.

23
00:01:35,920 --> 00:01:38,920
We will thoroughly cover the topic in another lesson dedicated to image optimization strategies.

24
00:01:42,720 --> 00:01:45,720
While minimizing the number of assets is useful,

25
00:01:46,160 --> 00:01:49,160
how they are loaded is just as important.

26
00:01:48,880 --> 00:01:51,880
From this perspective, a well-coded theme makes all the difference.

27
00:01:53,040 --> 00:01:56,040
Themes and plugins.

28
00:01:56,240 --> 00:01:59,240
Bloated themes that load too many assets are among the biggest culprits of poor performance scores.

29
00:02:01,600 --> 00:02:04,600
Similarly, the quality of the plugins you use influences how fast your site will perform,

30
00:02:07,680 --> 00:02:10,680
both objectively and perceivably.

31
00:02:10,640 --> 00:02:13,640
Plugins that perform excessive requests to external services,

32
00:02:15,840 --> 00:02:18,840
load multiple assets and constantly perform database queries will bog down even the best

33
00:02:21,600 --> 00:02:24,600
configured server. Embedded content and third-party elements.

34
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:29,000
Ads, analytics, social media widgets, alternative comments plugins,

35
00:02:32,320 --> 00:02:35,320
and externally hosted assets delay loading, slow down response times,

36
00:02:36,960 --> 00:02:39,960
hog bandwidth and may trigger higher bounce rates.

37
00:02:40,400 --> 00:02:43,400
Think twice before adding it into your site and be vigilant about the performance cost.

38
00:02:46,640 --> 00:02:49,640
How performance is measured?

39
00:02:48,240 --> 00:02:51,240
You can measure performance in two ways.

40
00:02:51,760 --> 00:02:54,760
Synthetic and real user monitoring or RUM.

41
00:02:55,280 --> 00:02:58,280
Both happens in the browser, but synthetic means running tests in the lab,

42
00:03:01,280 --> 00:03:04,280
under predefined conditions and preset variables.

43
00:03:04,080 --> 00:03:07,080
While RUM or RUM renders findings generated in the field, collecting data from actual site

44
00:03:12,320 --> 00:03:15,320
visitors. In either case, the tests would likely be based on a set of three metrics,

45
00:03:18,480 --> 00:03:21,480
outlined by Google and adopted across the industry as quality signals that are essential

46
00:03:24,240 --> 00:03:27,240
to delivering a great user experience on the web. They are known as core web vitals.

47
00:03:30,720 --> 00:03:33,720
So number one, LCP or largest contentful paint measures when the largest element on the page

48
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:41,000
becomes visible. Number two, CLS or cumulative layout shift, measures how much the elements on the page

49
00:03:46,400 --> 00:03:49,400
shift while the page is loading. And number three, INP, Interaction to Next Paint.

50
00:03:53,440 --> 00:03:56,440
A new addition to the list that measures how long it takes for the page to respond to user

51
00:03:59,280 --> 00:04:02,280
interactions. For example, clicks, taps and keyboard inputs.

52
00:04:04,640 --> 00:04:07,640
How to test your site? Testing helps you identify performance bottlenecks.

53
00:04:09,600 --> 00:04:12,600
You can do that using various tools, including page speed insights and web page test.

54
00:04:15,760 --> 00:04:18,760
Maintained by Google, PageSpeed Insights presents synthetic results alongside the company's

55
00:04:21,840 --> 00:04:24,840
version of RUM, the Chrome User Experience Report or CRUX. It will test the page on mobile and

56
00:04:28,880 --> 00:04:31,880
desktop devices and provides suggestions for improvements. Web Page Test is a more elaborate

57
00:04:35,840 --> 00:04:38,840
testing platform. It adds a bunch of helpful features on top of Google's metrics, including

58
00:04:41,680 --> 00:04:44,680
an environmental impact report, image analysis, a detailed breakdown of optimization opportunities

59
00:04:48,560 --> 00:04:51,560
and an option to select different locations, browsers and connection speeds.

60
00:04:54,000 --> 00:04:57,000
Running Web Page Test for the first time might be daunting, but it's an invaluable tool for

61
00:04:59,520 --> 00:05:02,520
testing and analyzing your site's overall performance. When testing, you'll encounter

62
00:05:05,120 --> 00:05:08,120
other software-driven metrics, including First Contentful Paint or FCP, when the browser displays

63
00:05:11,920 --> 00:05:14,920
the first bit of content, and then secondly, Total Blocking Time or TBT. The time elapsed

64
00:05:19,120 --> 00:05:22,120
after FCP and before visitors can interact with the site. These are influenced by a

65
00:05:25,280 --> 00:05:28,280
combination of loading too many assets and elements and failing to do so properly.

66
00:05:29,840 --> 00:05:32,840
Performance Lab is a community plugin developed by the WordPress Performance Team

67
00:05:36,000 --> 00:05:39,000
that might be able to mitigate some of these problems. This plugin combines six standalone

68
00:05:41,920 --> 00:05:44,920
plugins, each designated to tackle a specific performance feature using the latest browser

69
00:05:47,680 --> 00:05:50,680
technology. Once activated, the plugin automatically begins optimizing your site.

70
00:05:53,680 --> 00:05:56,680
There is no need for manual configuration or adjustments.

71
00:05:56,800 --> 00:05:59,800
The Importance of Hosting. The other factors affecting your site's speed are network infrastructure,

72
00:06:04,960 --> 00:06:07,960
server hardware and database operations. The metric that covers these is the Time to First

73
00:06:11,760 --> 00:06:14,760
Bite or TTFB, which measures the time it takes until the browser receives the first byte.

74
00:06:18,320 --> 00:06:21,320
This depends on the connection time of the visitor and the server.

75
00:06:22,320 --> 00:06:25,320
The faster the connection is established, the faster the bytes are sent, and the faster your site

76
00:06:28,560 --> 00:06:31,560
will load. Several factors determine the resource delivery speed, including geographical location,

77
00:06:35,520 --> 00:06:38,520
network conditions, hardware configuration and back-end processes. In other words,

78
00:06:41,280 --> 00:06:44,280
Hosting matters. As slow server response times can result from network or hardware issues,

79
00:06:47,280 --> 00:06:50,280
CPU, memory and storage speed, it's worth carefully considering every aspect of your hosting solution,

80
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:57,000
not just the price listed. Finally, Plugins. Performance plugins won't be able to reduce

81
00:07:00,480 --> 00:07:03,480
CPU load time on the server or update back-end software, but they can take care of things like

82
00:07:06,400 --> 00:07:09,400
CDNs, caching, compression, modification, database optimization and sometimes even security.

83
00:07:15,200 --> 00:07:18,200
So even when opting for more affordable shared hosting, it's a good idea to offset common

84
00:07:21,200 --> 00:07:24,200
challenges with the help of a trusted plugin that lets you use a CDN to minimize the client's

85
00:07:27,360 --> 00:07:30,360
server round trip times, apply caching to reduce the number of requests, and enable compression

86
00:07:34,480 --> 00:07:37,480
and modification to send the smallest amount of data.

87
00:07:37,360 --> 00:07:40,360
The WordPress Pplugin Directory features hundreds of performance and optimization plugins.

88
00:07:43,760 --> 00:07:46,760
Here are a few popular solutions. WP Optimize,

89
00:07:48,080 --> 00:07:51,080
W3 Total Cache, WP Super Cache, Jetback Boost and even Light Speed Cache.

90
00:07:56,560 --> 00:07:59,560
WordPress contributors have been working hard on improving speed and performance. Some features

91
00:08:03,280 --> 00:08:06,280
are included in Core, but others require users and developers to enable them.

92
00:08:07,840 --> 00:08:10,840
Make sure you're using the latest version of WordPress to benefit from the latest performance

93
00:08:13,120 --> 00:08:16,120
boosting techniques.

